nt of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Campo","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Antonio, Gaspare, Sal, Angelo, Carmine, Vito, Alfredo, Giuseppe, Marco, Rocco, Santino, Attilio.  Spanish Manuel, Carlos, Jose, Juan, Fernando, Ana, Enrique, Luis, Eduardo, Francisco.","Italian and Spanish: topographic name denoting someone who lived by a field, from <i>campo</i> ‘field, country(side)’ (from Latin <i>campus</i> ‘plain’), or a habitational name from any of numerous places called with this word. Compare Spanish   Del Campo  .","Altered form of French   Campeau  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Campillo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Pedro, Carlos, Luis, Abelardo, Acencion, Adriana, Beatriz, Benito, Celedonio, Graciela, Horacio.","Spanish: habitational name from any of various places called Campillo, from a diminutive of <i>campo</i> ‘field, country(side)’ (see   Campo  )."]},{"name":"Campi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Florio, Domenic, Enrico, Silvio.","Italian:","habitational name from any of various places called Campi, or a topographic name from the plural of <i>campo</i> ‘field’ (see   Campo  )."]},{"name":"Campise","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Gasper, Rocco, Gino, Sal, Salvatore.","Italian: nickname for a country dweller, from a derivative of   Campo  ."]},{"name":"Del Campo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Miguel, Armando, Carlos, Raul, Enrique, Margarita, Pedro, Alberto, Alfonso, Cesar.","Spanish: variant, with the preposition and definite article <i>del</i> ‘from the’, of   Campo   ‘field’."]},{"name":"Campisano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Caterina, Vito.","Italian (Sicily and Calabria): nickname for a countrydweller, from a derivative of   Campo  ."]},{"name":"Campese","meanings":["Italian: habitational name from any of numerous places called with <i>campo</i> or nickname for a country dweller, from a derivative of <i>campo</i> ‘field, country(side)’ (see   Campo  )."]},{"name":"Campellone","meanings":["Italian (Isernia, in Molise region): perhaps a habitational name from any of numerous places called Campello, from <i>campo</i> ‘field, country(side)’ (see   Campo  )."]},{"name":"Campolo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Fortunato, Silvio.","Italian (Calabria): topographic name from medieval Latin <i>campulus</i> ‘little field’, a diminutive of   Campo  ."]},{"name":"Campitelli","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Enrico, Antonio, Carlo, Florentino, Guido, Oswaldo, Reinaldo.","Italian: probably a habitational name from any of various places called Campitelli or Campitello; otherwise possibly from a diminutive of <b>Campiti</b>, an adjectival form of   Campo  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thoried De Campo was born in 1100, in Italy, his father, Cederick de Campo, was 44 and his mother, Iona, was 35. He had at least 1 son with Magdalena. He died in 1160, in Normandy, France, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1100–1160":"1100–1160","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","1135–1175":"1135–1175","1056–1110":"1056–1110","1065–Female":"1065–Surnud","1135":"1135","1100":"1100","1056":"1056","1110":"1110","1065":"1065","1175":"1175","1160":"1160","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Italy":"Itaalia","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1100–1160":"1100–1160","1110–Female":"1110–Kuollut","1135–1175":"1135–1175","1056–1110":"1056–1110","1065–Female":"1065–Kuollut","1135":"1135","1100":"1100","1056":"1056","1110":"1110","1065":"1065","1175":"1175","1160":"1160","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Ranska","Italy":"Italia","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":